{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-be755020fd9c22bd", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t \n2\t\n3\t Scalable Keyword Spotting via Modular Network Expansion \n4\t\n5\t Report GitHub Issue \n6\t × \n7\t\n8\t Title: \n9\t\n10\t Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: \n11\t\n12\t Description: \n13\t\n14\t Submit without GitHub \n15\t Submit in GitHub \n16\t\n17\t arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n18\t Learn more \n19\t × \n20\t\n21\t Back to arXiv \n22\t\n23\t Why HTML? \n24\t\n25\t Report Issue \n26\t\n27\t Back to Abstract \n28\t\n29\t Download PDF \n30\t\n31\t Abstract \n32\t 1 Introduction \n33\t 2 Related work \n34\t\n35\t 3 Methodology \n36\t\n37\t 3.1 Problem setup \n38\t 3.2 Base architecture \n39\t 3.3 Modular expansion \n40\t 3.4 Inference: core-first decision rule \n41\t 3.5 Baselines \n42\t\n43\t 4 Experiments \n44\t\n45\t 4.1 Datasets and expansion tasks \n46\t 4.2 Features and training setup \n47\t 4.3 Metric, thresholds, and confidence intervals \n48\t 4.4 Comparative analysis \n49\t 4.5 Ablation Study: Expansion Depth \n50\t\n51\t 5 Conclusion \n52\t 6 Generative AI Use Disclosure \n53\t References \n54\t\n55\t License: CC BY-SA 4.0\n56\t\n57\tarXiv:2607.19918v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026 \n58\t\n59\t Khaymonenko\n60\tSaladukha\n61\tRak\n62\tRostov\n63\t\n64\t Scalable Keyword Spotting via Modular Network Expansion \n65\t\n66\t Viktor\n67\t\n68\t Dzmitry\n69\t\n70\t Aliaksei\n71\t\n72\t Alexander\n73\t\n74\t 1 Embedded Voice Input Team, Yandex, Russia \n75\t 2 Embedded Voice Input Team, Yandex, Belarus\n76\t\n77\t khaymonenko@yandex-team.ru, dsoloduha@yandex-team.ru, alexrak@yandex-team.ru, a-rostov@yandex-team.ru \n78\t\n79\t Abstract \n80\t Keyword spotting (KWS) models on embedded devices often need to add new keywords after deployment, but updates are difficult when original training data are unavailable and regressions on existing triggers are unacceptable. \n81\t At a fixed operating point, our method reduces average new-keyword false reject rate (FRR) from 6.46% to 4.37% versus a parameter-matched separate-model baseline and outperforms parameter-efficient tuning baselines (adapters, LoRA), while using fewer multiply-accumulate operations (MACs) under the same added-parameter budget (\\leq10k): 16.34M vs 18.45M / 20.52M . \n82\t We achieve this via parameter-capped modular expansion: the base network, including batch-normalization statistics and the core classifier, is frozen, and only a lightweight expansion branch with a separate new-keyword head is trained, preserving core logits, shipped outputs, and thresholds for existing keywords. \n83\t\n84\t keywords: keyword spotting, continuous learning, catastrophic forgetting, modular neural networks\n85\t\n86\t 1 Introduction \n87\t\n88\t Keyword spotting enables hands-free interaction on resource-constrained devices, where small-footprint models must remain accurate and reliable across speakers and acoustic conditions [ sainath15b_interspeech , kim21_interspeech , saladukha25_interspeech ] . In deployed products, keyword inventories can change over time as new features, locales, or user needs emerge. Updating a fixed-vocabulary KWS model in this setting is difficult: the original training data may be unavailable (e.g., due to privacy or storage constraints), full retraining is compute-intensive, and, more critically, it can introduce regressions on keywords that users already rely on. Open-vocabulary and few-shot approaches reduce the need for retraining, but they often lag behind fixed-vocabulary systems in robustness, especially under noise and for phonetically similar commands. In this work, we focus on small-footprint embedded KWS and study class-incremental keyword expansion : adding new triggers after deployment under strict update safety constraints. \n89\t\n90\t We target an expansion setting with two practical constraints: the original training data are unavailable during the update, and the updated system must not degrade performance on previously supported keywords. To meet these constraints, we freeze the entire pretrained KWS model, including batch-normalization parameters and statistics, and attach a lightweight trainable expansion path with a separate classifier head for the new keywords. The expansion adds at most 10k parameters to a 150k-parameter base model and is trained only on new-keyword data. Because the base path is unchanged, the logits for the original keyword set are identical to those of the pretrained model for any input, providing a strict non-regression guarantee by construction. \n91\t\n92\t Experiments on Google Speech Commands v2 (GSC) [ warden2018speech ] demonstrate that this safety guarantee does not prevent effective expansion: under a 10k-parameter budget, modular expansion improves new-keyword detection relative to parameter-matched baselines (including a separate-model deployment baseline, continual-learning methods, and parameter-efficient fine-tuning), while preserving the shipped core detector exactly. \n93\t\n94\t 2 Related work \n95\t\n96\t Keyword spotting has been widely studied due to its importance in always-on voice interfaces. Most deployed systems use a fixed vocabulary and train compact neural classifiers, including CNN-based architectures and streaming-friendly designs such as SVDF models [ sainath15b_interspeech , arik17_interspeech , zhuang16_interspeech , alvarez19_icassp ] . These models achieve strong accuracy under tight latency and memory constraints, but extending the label set typically requires retraining and careful class balancing, and updates may introduce regressions on previously supported keywords. \n97\t\n98\t To improve flexibility, open-vocabulary and query-based KWS methods have been explored [ chen15_icassp , jung25b_interspeech ] . These approaches enable detecting user-specified phrases, but in embedded settings they may trade off accuracy and robustness relative to fixed-vocabulary systems, particularly under noise or when distinguishing phonetically similar triggers. \n99\t\n100\t Another direction is fast adaptation via transfer learning and few-shot learning. Metric-based approaches, including prototypical networks and related embedding methods [ parnami_2022 , huh21_slt ] , can add new keywords with limited labeled audio. However, maintaining stable performance on the original keyword set remains challenging when the model is updated, especially when the original training data are unavailable. \n101\t\n102\t Continual learning methods aim to reduce catastrophic forgetting during incremental updates. Regularization-based approaches such as EWC and LwF [ kirkpatrick17_nas , li2018 ] constrain parameter drift, while replay-based methods rehearse past data or generated samples [ shin17_nips , rolnick19_nips ] . In practice, these methods typically provide soft protection rather than a strict non-regression guarantee, and replay is incompatible with settings where the original training data cannot be stored or reused. Parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods (e.g., adapters or LoRA [ houlsby2019_corr , hu2021_corr ] ) reduce the number of trainable parameters, but they still alter the shared computation path and therefore cannot guarantee unchanged behavior on existing keywords; retaining the original behavior may also require extra inference compute. \n103\t\n104\t Progressive Neural Networks (PNNs) [ rusu16_arxiv ] address task-incremental learning by freezing previous columns and adding a new column with lateral connections, typically assuming that the task identity (and thus which column to execute) is known at inference time. In contrast, we study class-incremental expansion of a single always-on, fixed-latency embedded KWS detector, where (i) the original training data are unavailable, (ii) model growth must be strictly bounded, and (iii) the shipped detector’s outputs and threshold-based decision rule for existing keywords must remain exactly unchanged for all inputs. Concretely, we freeze the entire deployed network (including batch-normalization statistics) and attach a single parameter-capped (\\leq10k) expansion branch and a separate head for the new keywords, enabling non-regression by construction. \n105\t\n106\t 3 Methodology \n107\t\n108\t 3.1 Problem setup \n109\t\n110\t Let x denote an input audio utterance. Let \\mathcal{Y}_{1} denote the set of deployed (core) keywords and \\mathcal{Y}_{2} a disjoint set of new keywords, with \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cap\\mathcal{Y}_{2}=\\varnothing. We use a single background label \\emptyset to denote ``none of the keywords of interest.'' \n111\t\n112\t A base model f_{\\mathrm{base}}(x;\\theta_{\\mathrm{base}}) is trained on a dataset D_{1} with labels in \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. We are then given a second dataset D_{2} with labels in \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\} and no access to D_{1} during expansion. \n113\t\n114\t We seek an expanded model f_{\\mathrm{exp}}(x;\\theta_{\\mathrm{base}},\\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}) that adds a small number of parameters \\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}, is trained only on D_{2}, and satisfies a strict non-regression property on \\mathcal{Y}_{1} while maximizing performance on \\mathcal{Y}_{2}. \n115\t\n116\t (a) Base model \n117\t\n118\t (b) Encoder Block \n119\t\n120\t Figure 1: Base model and Encoder Block for core-keyword classification. \n121\t\n122\t (a) Expanded model \n123\t\n124\t (b) Expanded Block \n125\t\n126\t Figure 2: Expanded model. Each Expanded Block taps a frozen Base Block activation, merges it with the previous expanded state, and applies a lightweight residual transform. \n127\t\n128\t 3.2 Base architecture \n129\t\n130\t Base network follows a small-footprint SVDF-style architecture  [ alvarez19_icassp , nakkiran15_interspeech ] . Each Base (Encoder) Block applies SVDF, followed by batch-normalization (BN) [ ioffe15_pmlr ] , hard-swish  [ howard19_iccv ] , and dropout  [ hinton12_corr ] . The encoder output is temporally pooled and passed to an Core Head classifier producing logits\n131\t\\ell_{\\mathrm{core}}^{\\mathrm{base}}(x)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{|\\mathcal{Y}_{1}|+1}\n132\tover \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, followed by softmax. The base model has approximately 150k parameters (Fig.  1 ). \n133\t\n134\t 3.3 Modular expansion \n135\t\n136\t We freeze the entire base path (including BN affine parameters and running statistics) and attach a lightweight, trainable expansion path composed of L Expanded Blocks plus a New Head that predicts logits \\ell_{\\mathrm{new}}(x) over \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\} (Fig.  2 ). Expanded Blocks tap selected frozen Base Block activations (and optionally the previous Expanded Block output) and apply a small residual transform; the total added parameters (Expanded Blocks + New Head) are capped at 10k (final model \\sim160k parameters). \n137\t\n138\t Each Expanded Block takes the activation from a frozen Base Block and the previous Expanded Block output, concatenates them along the channel dimension, and applies a lightweight transform consisting of a 1D convolution (Conv1D over time, implemented as a small-kernel temporal conv), followed by batch-normalization and hard-swish.\n139\tThe first Expanded Block is a special case: it takes only the frozen encoder activation (no previous expanded output), so the concatenation reduces to an identity.\n140\tThe block output is then used as input to the next Expanded Block, and the final Expanded Block output is temporally pooled and fed to the New Head. \n141\t\n142\t The expanded model outputs \n143\t\n144\t \\displaystyle p_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) \n145\t \\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}(\\ell_{\\mathrm{core}}(x)),\\quad y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, \n146\t\n147\t (1) \n148\t\n149\t \\displaystyle p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x) \n150\t \\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}(\\ell_{\\mathrm{new}}(x)),\\quad y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. \n151\t\n152\t (2) \n153\t\n154\t Since the Core Head computation is frozen and does not depend on the expansion path, for all x: \n155\t\n156\t \\displaystyle\\ell^{\\mathrm{exp}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x) \n157\t \\displaystyle\\equiv\\ell^{\\mathrm{base}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x), \n158\t\n159\t (3) \n160\t\n161\t \\displaystyle\\Rightarrow\\quad p^{\\mathrm{exp}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) \n162\t \\displaystyle\\equiv p^{\\mathrm{base}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x),\\quad\\forall y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. \n163\t\n164\t Training uses only D_{2} and updates only \\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}} by minimizing cross-entropy on the New Head: \n165\t\n166\t \\min_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}}\\ \\ \\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\\sim D_{2}}\\left[-\\log p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x)\\right]. \n167\t\n168\t (4) \n169\t\n170\t Table 1: Model size and the worst-case compute cost under the deployed inference pipeline (core-first decision rule) for 1-second utterance. \n171\t\n172\t Method \n173\t Params (K) \n174\t MACs (M) \n175\t Rel. MACs \n176\t\n177\t Base Model \n178\t 150 \n179\t 15.08 \n180\t 1.00\\times \n181\t\n182\t Full Finetune \n183\t 150 \n184\t 15.08 \n185\t 1.00\\times \n186\t\n187\t EWC \n188\t 150 \n189\t 15.08 \n190\t 1.00\\times \n191\t\n192\t Head-Only \n193\t 151 \n194\t 15.16 \n195\t 1.01\\times \n196\t\n197\t Ensemble \n198\t 160 \n199\t 16.14 \n200\t 1.07\\times \n201\t\n202\t Adapters \n203\t 160 \n204\t 18.45 \n205\t 1.22\\times \n206\t\n207\t LoRA \n208\t 160 \n209\t 20.52 \n210\t 1.36\\times \n211\t\n212\t Proposed \n213\t 160 \n214\t 16.34 \n215\t 1.08\\times \n216\t\n217\t 3.4 Inference: core-first decision rule \n218\t\n219\t In a deployed KWS system, preserving the shipped behavior means preserving the\n220\t decision rule of the original detector for the core label set\n221\t\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, not only its logits.\n222\tWe therefore use a core-first decision rule. \n223\t\n224\t Let s^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y}(x)=p_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\n225\tand let \\tau^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y} denote the same per-keyword thresholds\n226\tused by the shipped model.\n227\tThe core detector outputs \n228\t\n229\t \\displaystyle y_{core}^{*}(x) \n230\t \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}}s^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y}(x), \n231\t\n232\t (5) \n233\t\n234\t \\displaystyle\\hat{y}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x) \n235\t \\displaystyle= \n236\t\n237\t Only if the core detector rejects (outputs \\emptyset) do we evaluate the new head.\n238\tLet s^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}(x)=p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x) for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}\n239\twith thresholds \\tau^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}. The expanded system outputs \n240\t\n241\t \\displaystyle y_{\\mathrm{new}}^{*}(x) \n242\t \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}}s^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}(x), \n243\t\n244\t (6) \n245\t\n246\t \\displaystyle\\hat{y}(x) \n247\t \\displaystyle= \n248\t\n249\t 3.5 Baselines \n250\t\n251\t We compare against four baseline families that differ in whether they modify the\n252\tshipped core detector and whether they can provide a strict non-regression\n253\tguarantee. Unless stated otherwise, adaptation uses only D_{2} and all methods\n254\tthat add capacity are constrained to \\leq10k new parameters. For completeness,\n255\tTable  1 reports the parameter count and worst-case compute\n256\tcost in multiply-accumulate operations (MACs) for each method under the deployed core-first inference pipeline; we\n257\tuse these values to budget-match baselines and to quantify inference overhead. \n258\t\n259\t Unconstrained model updates. \n260\t Full Finetune continues training the base model on D_{2} by updating\n261\tall parameters with cross-entropy over \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}.\n262\tThis serves as a reference for fitting the new keywords, but it generally\n263\tintroduces catastrophic forgetting on \\mathcal{Y}_{1}. \n264\t\n265\t Core-invariant expansions (safe by construction). \n266\t Head-Only trains only a new classifier head on top of the frozen base\n267\trepresentation (our method with L{=}0). Ensemble trains an independent\n268\t\\sim10k-parameter model on D_{2} and combines it with the shipped detector using\n269\tthe same core-first decision rule at inference. Both approaches preserve the core\n270\tdetector exactly, but Head-only often lacks capacity, while Ensemble does not\n271\treuse the base model’s intermediate features. \n272\t\n273\t Parameter-efficient tuning with a forked branch. \n274\t Adapters and LoRA introduce trainable modules in a parallel\n275\ttop-L branch that feeds the New Head, while the original Core Head continues to\n276\tuse the frozen base path. We choose L (and LoRA ranks) to match the additional\n277\tinference compute of our expansion under the same 10k-parameter budget. \n278\t\n279\t Relaxed-constraint continual learning. \n280\t EWC is included for context: it regularizes fine-tuning using Fisher\n281\tinformation estimated from D_{1} and therefore does not strictly satisfy the\n282\tno-access-to-D_{1} setting; we use \\lambda=5\\times 10^{5} in all experiments. \n283\t\n284\t Table 2: Macro FRR (%) on GSC test at thresholds calibrated to 1% FAR on CV,\n285\tevaluated with the core-first decision rule. \n286\t\n287\t {left, right} \n288\t {on, off} \n289\t {stop, go} \n290\t {up, down} \n291\t {yes, no} \n292\t Avg. \n293\t\n294\t Core Phrases \n295\t\n296\t Base Model \n297\t\n298\t 2.37 (±0.24) \n299\t\n300\t 2.42 (±0.31) \n301\t\n302\t 3.29 (±0.55) \n303\t\n304\t 2.63 (±0.28) \n305\t\n306\t 2.83 (±0.12) \n307\t\n308\t 2.71 (±0.12) \n309\t\n310\t Full Finetune \n311\t 82.94 (±2.64) \n312\t\n313\t 79.68 (±7.79) \n314\t\n315\t 67.94 (±6.30) \n316\t\n317\t 54.33 (±13.55) \n318\t\n319\t 60.52 (±5.81) \n320\t\n321\t 69.08 (±1.98) \n322\t\n323\t EWC \n324\t 7.07 (±0.62) \n325\t\n326\t 5.02 (±0.32) \n327\t\n328\t 3.06 (±0.53) \n329\t\n330\t 2.63 (±0.24) \n331\t\n332\t 4.56 (±0.16) \n333\t\n334\t 4.47 (±0.18) \n335\t\n336\t New Phrases \n337\t\n338\t Full Finetune \n339\t 2.86 (±0.48) \n340\t\n341\t 2.14 (±0.46) \n342\t\n343\t 1.60 (±0.50) \n344\t\n345\t 3.33 (±0.70) \n346\t\n347\t 1.82 (±0.47) \n348\t\n349\t 2.35 (±0.27) \n350\t\n351\t Head-Only \n352\t 42.55 (±16.44) \n353\t\n354\t 28.11 (±11.68) \n355\t\n356\t 18.61 (±10.88) \n357\t\n358\t 12.13 (±2.43) \n359\t\n360\t 10.11 (±2.20) \n361\t\n362\t 22.30 (±4.27) \n363\t\n364\t Ensemble \n365\t 8.77 (±2.00) \n366\t\n367\t 3.81 (±0.99) \n368\t\n369\t 6.68 (±1.91) \n370\t\n371\t 5.82 (±0.73) \n372\t\n373\t 7.21 (±1.17) \n374\t\n375\t 6.46 (±0.42) \n376\t\n377\t EWC \n378\t\n379\t 5.44 (±0.40) \n380\t\n381\t 6.97 (±1.08) \n382\t\n383\t 5.96 (±0.57) \n384\t\n385\t 12.28 (±1.89) \n386\t\n387\t 9.09 (±1.18) \n388\t\n389\t 7.95 (±0.64) \n390\t\n391\t Adapters \n392\t 13.38 (±1.68) \n393\t\n394\t 8.95 (±1.61) \n395\t\n396\t 6.68 (±2.01) \n397\t\n398\t 5.74 (±0.65) \n399\t\n400\t 5.52 (±0.80) \n401\t\n402\t 8.05 (±0.35) \n403\t\n404\t LoRA \n405\t 9.88 (±1.36) \n406\t\n407\t 5.84 (±1.28) \n408\t\n409\t 6.61 (±2.11) \n410\t\n411\t 5.12 (±1.78) \n412\t\n413\t 4.61 (±0.86) \n414\t\n415\t 6.41 (±0.66) \n416\t\n417\t Proposed \n418\t 6.69 (±1.04) \n419\t\n420\t 2.68 (±0.39) \n421\t\n422\t 4.56 (±0.86) \n423\t\n424\t 4.57 (±0.73) \n425\t\n426\t 3.36 (±0.38) \n427\t\n428\t 4.37 (±0.33) \n429\t\n430\t Figure 3: New-keyword FRR (%) vs. Expanded Blocks L for \\mathcal{Y}_{2}=\\{\\textit{left,right}\\}. \n431\t\n432\t 4 Experiments \n433\t\n434\t 4.1 Datasets and expansion tasks \n435\t\n436\t Experiments are conducted on Google Speech Commands v2 (GSC) using the official train/validation/test splits. The target vocabulary is the standard set of 10 commands\n437\t{ left, right, on, off, stop, go, up, down, yes, no }.\n438\tAll other words in GSC, together with silence segments, are mapped to the background label \\emptyset. \n439\t\n440\t Keyword expansion is evaluated through five held-out pairs to reduce sensitivity to any single keyword choice and to cover a range of confusability patterns. For each task, one command pair is designated as the new set \\mathcal{Y}_{2} and the remaining eight commands form the deployed core set \\mathcal{Y}_{1}. The held-out pairs are\n441\t{left, right}, {on, off}, {stop, go}, {up, down}, and {yes, no}.\n442\tA base model is trained on D_{1} (GSC train restricted to \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}). The expansion stage then uses only D_{2} (GSC train restricted to \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}), with no access to the original D_{1} audio. \n443\t\n444\t To obtain a less biased negative distribution than GSC itself, Mozilla Common Voice v17 (CV) [ ardila-etal-2020-common ] is used as a negative-only corpus. In all reported results, positives come from the GSC test split, while negatives for FAR calibration come from the CV test split. \n445\t\n446\t 4.2 Features and training setup \n447\t\n448\t Audio is 16 kHz mono. Input features are 40-bin log-mel filterbanks computed with a 25 ms window and 10 ms hop. To improve robustness to channel and speaking-style variability, training applies SpecAugment [ park19e_interspeech ] directly on the log-mel features (time masking and frequency masking). \n449\t\n450\t Optimization uses Adam [ kingma14_iclr ] with a cosine learning-rate schedule [ loshchilov17_iclr ] . Base Models are trained for 40 epochs on D_{1}. Expansion training runs for 10 epochs on D_{2}. For modular methods (including the proposed one), only the newly added parameters are updated during expansion; the base path is kept frozen, including batch-normalization affine parameters and running statistics. Methods that introduce new capacity are constrained to an added-parameter budget of \\leq10k. \n451\t\n452\t 4.3 Metric, thresholds, and confidence intervals \n453\t\n454\t Performance is reported as macro false reject rate (FRR) at a fixed false accept rate (FAR) operating point. For each keyword y, a threshold \\tau_{y} is chosen to match 1% FAR on the CV test partition, using the corresponding keyword score (Core Head for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}, New Head for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}). \n455\t\n456\t Given calibrated thresholds, FRR is computed on the GSC test split. Reported values are macro-averaged across the keywords in the evaluated set (core or new). \n457\t\n458\t Each (method, keyword-pair) configuration is repeated with 8 independent runs (different random seeds). Table  2 reports the sample mean and a 95% confidence interval estimated via a t-statistic:\n459\t\\bar{x}\\ \\pm\\ t_{0.975,7}\\,s/\\sqrt{8},\n460\twhere s is the sample standard deviation across runs. \n461\t\n462\t 4.4 Comparative analysis \n463\t\n464\t Table  2 reports macro FRR (%) on GSC positives with\n465\tthresholds calibrated to 1% FAR on CV negatives (95% confidence intervals in\n466\tparentheses). \n467\t\n468\t The Base Model achieves low FRR on the core vocabulary (from 2.37% to 3.29%,\n469\t2.71% on average). The Core Phrases section includes only methods that\n470\tcan change the shipped detector (Full Fine-tuning and EWC). Adapters, LoRA,\n471\tEnsemble, and the proposed method freeze the core path, so their core results\n472\tmatch the Base Model exactly and are omitted to avoid repeating identical\n473\tnumbers. \n474\t\n475\t Full Fine-tuning fits the new phrases well (2.35% average FRR) but catastrophically\n476\tregresses the core vocabulary, increasing average core FRR from 2.71% \n477\tto 69.08% . EWC mitigates forgetting but still increases core FRR to\n478\t 4.47% ; on new phrases it reaches 7.95% on average (best case\n479\t5.44% on {left, right}). We include EWC for context, although it relies on\n480\tinformation derived from D_{1} (or precomputed Fisher statistics) and thus\n481\tviolates the strict no-D_{1} setting. \n482\t\n483\t Among methods that satisfy the deployment constraints, Head-Only performs poorly\n484\ton new keywords ( 22.30% average FRR). Parameter-efficient baselines\n485\timprove substantially, with Adapters at 8.05% and LoRA at\n486\t 6.41% . Ensemble is a strong deployment baseline that adds an\n487\tindependent \\sim10k-parameter model for \\mathcal{Y}_{2}, achieving\n488\t 6.46% . Modular expansion further improves new-keyword detection under\n489\tthe same parameter budget, reducing average FRR to 4.37% (an absolute\n490\tgain of 2.09 points). \n491\t\n492\t 4.5 Ablation Study: Expansion Depth \n493\t\n494\t We analyze the impact of feature reuse depth in Figure 3 , which plots new-keyword FRR against the number of tapped blocks in the expansion path. Tapping only shallow layers (1–3 blocks) yields high error rates, suggesting insufficient semantic abstraction. Conversely, extending the expansion to four blocks minimizes the median FRR. Beyond this point, performance plateaus or slightly degrades, indicating that the deepest layers of the base network are overly specialized to the core vocabulary Y_{1} and provide limited transfer utility. Consequently, we adopt the four-block expansion as the optimal configuration for all reported comparisons. \n495\t\n496\t 5 Conclusion \n497\t\n498\t On-device KWS systems must evolve as products add features and languages, yet\n499\tupdates are challenging when the original training audio cannot be reused and\n500\tregressions on existing keywords are unacceptable. \n501\t\n502\t We presented a modular expansion mechanism that adds new keywords without\n503\ttouching the deployed detector. The full base network is kept frozen (including\n504\tbatch-normalization statistics), and new functionality is introduced through a\n505\tsmall attached branch and a separate new-keyword head (up to 10k parameters),\n506\tkeeping the core detector’s logits and threshold behavior exactly unchanged. \n507\t\n508\t On Google Speech Commands (thresholds calibrated at 1% FAR using Common Voice),\n509\tthe expanded model improves average new-keyword FRR from 6.46% to\n510\t 4.37% versus a parameter-matched separate-model baseline and also\n511\toutperforms adapter- and LoRA-based tuning. It further uses fewer worst-case\n512\tMACs under the deployed core-first pipeline ( 16.34M ) than adapters\n513\t( 18.45M ) and LoRA ( 20.52M ) at the same added-parameter budget. Together, these results\n514\tsupport modular expansion as a practical way to scale embedded KWS vocabularies\n515\twhile preserving the shipped user experience. \n516\t\n517\t Multi-stage expansion, where new keyword sets are added sequentially, is a\n518\tnatural direction for future work, especially under tight parameter and latency budgets. \n519\t\n520\t 6 Generative AI Use Disclosure \n521\t\n522\t We used ChatGPT (OpenAI; GPT-5.2) to assist with English editing and polishing of the manuscript. All technical content, experiments, and conclusions were produced and verified by the authors. \n523\t\n524\t References \n525\t\n526\t Experimental support, please\n527\t view the build logs \n528\t for errors. Generated by\n529\t\n530\t L\n531\t A \n532\t T\n533\t E \n534\t\n535\t xml \n536\t\n537\t .\n538\t\n539\t Instructions for reporting errors \n540\t We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile\n541\t support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the\n542\t methods listed below: \n543\t\n544\t Click the \"Report Issue\" ( \n545\t\n546\t ) button, located in the page header. \n547\t\n548\t Tip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report. \n549\t Our team has already identified the following issues . We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we\n550\t may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability\n551\t should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for\n552\t all. \n553\t Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion , and welcome developer contributions . \n554\t\n555\t We gratefully acknowledge support from\n556\t our major funders ,\n557\t member institutions , ,\n558\t and all contributors.\n559\t\n560\t About \n561\t · \n562\t Help \n563\t · \n564\t Contact \n565\t · \n566\t Subscribe \n567\t · \n568\t Copyright \n569\t · \n570\t Privacy \n571\t · \n572\t Accessibility \n573\t · \n574\t Operational Status (opens in new tab) \n575\t\n576\t Major funding support from \n577\t\n578\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "661d7789-02a0-4faf-820e-46fe5b9e77f1", "uuid": "47e7e607-5d5e-4ad1-be57-35853f2085f1", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T06:32:13.304Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/kws_paper.txt", "content": " \n\n Scalable Keyword Spotting via Modular Network Expansion \n\n Report GitHub Issue \n × \n\n Title: \n\n Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: \n\n Description: \n\n Submit without GitHub \n Submit in GitHub \n\n arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n Learn more \n × \n\n Back to arXiv \n\n Why HTML? \n\n Report Issue \n\n Back to Abstract \n\n Download PDF \n\n Abstract \n 1 Introduction \n 2 Related work \n\n 3 Methodology \n\n 3.1 Problem setup \n 3.2 Base architecture \n 3.3 Modular expansion \n 3.4 Inference: core-first decision rule \n 3.5 Baselines \n\n 4 Experiments \n\n 4.1 Datasets and expansion tasks \n 4.2 Features and training setup \n 4.3 Metric, thresholds, and confidence intervals \n 4.4 Comparative analysis \n 4.5 Ablation Study: Expansion Depth \n\n 5 Conclusion \n 6 Generative AI Use Disclosure \n References \n\n License: CC BY-SA 4.0\n\narXiv:2607.19918v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026 \n\n Khaymonenko\nSaladukha\nRak\nRostov\n\n Scalable Keyword Spotting via Modular Network Expansion \n\n Viktor\n\n Dzmitry\n\n Aliaksei\n\n Alexander\n\n 1 Embedded Voice Input Team, Yandex, Russia \n 2 Embedded Voice Input Team, Yandex, Belarus\n\n khaymonenko@yandex-team.ru, dsoloduha@yandex-team.ru, alexrak@yandex-team.ru, a-rostov@yandex-team.ru \n\n Abstract \n Keyword spotting (KWS) models on embedded devices often need to add new keywords after deployment, but updates are difficult when original training data are unavailable and regressions on existing triggers are unacceptable. \n At a fixed operating point, our method reduces average new-keyword false reject rate (FRR) from 6.46% to 4.37% versus a parameter-matched separate-model baseline and outperforms parameter-efficient tuning baselines (adapters, LoRA), while using fewer multiply-accumulate operations (MACs) under the same added-parameter budget (\\leq10k): 16.34M vs 18.45M / 20.52M . \n We achieve this via parameter-capped modular expansion: the base network, including batch-normalization statistics and the core classifier, is frozen, and only a lightweight expansion branch with a separate new-keyword head is trained, preserving core logits, shipped outputs, and thresholds for existing keywords. \n\n keywords: keyword spotting, continuous learning, catastrophic forgetting, modular neural networks\n\n 1 Introduction \n\n Keyword spotting enables hands-free interaction on resource-constrained devices, where small-footprint models must remain accurate and reliable across speakers and acoustic conditions [ sainath15b_interspeech , kim21_interspeech , saladukha25_interspeech ] . In deployed products, keyword inventories can change over time as new features, locales, or user needs emerge. Updating a fixed-vocabulary KWS model in this setting is difficult: the original training data may be unavailable (e.g., due to privacy or storage constraints), full retraining is compute-intensive, and, more critically, it can introduce regressions on keywords that users already rely on. Open-vocabulary and few-shot approaches reduce the need for retraining, but they often lag behind fixed-vocabulary systems in robustness, especially under noise and for phonetically similar commands. In this work, we focus on small-footprint embedded KWS and study class-incremental keyword expansion : adding new triggers after deployment under strict update safety constraints. \n\n We target an expansion setting with two practical constraints: the original training data are unavailable during the update, and the updated system must not degrade performance on previously supported keywords. To meet these constraints, we freeze the entire pretrained KWS model, including batch-normalization parameters and statistics, and attach a lightweight trainable expansion path with a separate classifier head for the new keywords. The expansion adds at most 10k parameters to a 150k-parameter base model and is trained only on new-keyword data. Because the base path is unchanged, the logits for the original keyword set are identical to those of the pretrained model for any input, providing a strict non-regression guarantee by construction. \n\n Experiments on Google Speech Commands v2 (GSC) [ warden2018speech ] demonstrate that this safety guarantee does not prevent effective expansion: under a 10k-parameter budget, modular expansion improves new-keyword detection relative to parameter-matched baselines (including a separate-model deployment baseline, continual-learning methods, and parameter-efficient fine-tuning), while preserving the shipped core detector exactly. \n\n 2 Related work \n\n Keyword spotting has been widely studied due to its importance in always-on voice interfaces. Most deployed systems use a fixed vocabulary and train compact neural classifiers, including CNN-based architectures and streaming-friendly designs such as SVDF models [ sainath15b_interspeech , arik17_interspeech , zhuang16_interspeech , alvarez19_icassp ] . These models achieve strong accuracy under tight latency and memory constraints, but extending the label set typically requires retraining and careful class balancing, and updates may introduce regressions on previously supported keywords. \n\n To improve flexibility, open-vocabulary and query-based KWS methods have been explored [ chen15_icassp , jung25b_interspeech ] . These approaches enable detecting user-specified phrases, but in embedded settings they may trade off accuracy and robustness relative to fixed-vocabulary systems, particularly under noise or when distinguishing phonetically similar triggers. \n\n Another direction is fast adaptation via transfer learning and few-shot learning. Metric-based approaches, including prototypical networks and related embedding methods [ parnami_2022 , huh21_slt ] , can add new keywords with limited labeled audio. However, maintaining stable performance on the original keyword set remains challenging when the model is updated, especially when the original training data are unavailable. \n\n Continual learning methods aim to reduce catastrophic forgetting during incremental updates. Regularization-based approaches such as EWC and LwF [ kirkpatrick17_nas , li2018 ] constrain parameter drift, while replay-based methods rehearse past data or generated samples [ shin17_nips , rolnick19_nips ] . In practice, these methods typically provide soft protection rather than a strict non-regression guarantee, and replay is incompatible with settings where the original training data cannot be stored or reused. Parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods (e.g., adapters or LoRA [ houlsby2019_corr , hu2021_corr ] ) reduce the number of trainable parameters, but they still alter the shared computation path and therefore cannot guarantee unchanged behavior on existing keywords; retaining the original behavior may also require extra inference compute. \n\n Progressive Neural Networks (PNNs) [ rusu16_arxiv ] address task-incremental learning by freezing previous columns and adding a new column with lateral connections, typically assuming that the task identity (and thus which column to execute) is known at inference time. In contrast, we study class-incremental expansion of a single always-on, fixed-latency embedded KWS detector, where (i) the original training data are unavailable, (ii) model growth must be strictly bounded, and (iii) the shipped detector’s outputs and threshold-based decision rule for existing keywords must remain exactly unchanged for all inputs. Concretely, we freeze the entire deployed network (including batch-normalization statistics) and attach a single parameter-capped (\\leq10k) expansion branch and a separate head for the new keywords, enabling non-regression by construction. \n\n 3 Methodology \n\n 3.1 Problem setup \n\n Let x denote an input audio utterance. Let \\mathcal{Y}_{1} denote the set of deployed (core) keywords and \\mathcal{Y}_{2} a disjoint set of new keywords, with \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cap\\mathcal{Y}_{2}=\\varnothing. We use a single background label \\emptyset to denote ``none of the keywords of interest.'' \n\n A base model f_{\\mathrm{base}}(x;\\theta_{\\mathrm{base}}) is trained on a dataset D_{1} with labels in \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. We are then given a second dataset D_{2} with labels in \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\} and no access to D_{1} during expansion. \n\n We seek an expanded model f_{\\mathrm{exp}}(x;\\theta_{\\mathrm{base}},\\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}) that adds a small number of parameters \\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}, is trained only on D_{2}, and satisfies a strict non-regression property on \\mathcal{Y}_{1} while maximizing performance on \\mathcal{Y}_{2}. \n\n (a) Base model \n\n (b) Encoder Block \n\n Figure 1: Base model and Encoder Block for core-keyword classification. \n\n (a) Expanded model \n\n (b) Expanded Block \n\n Figure 2: Expanded model. Each Expanded Block taps a frozen Base Block activation, merges it with the previous expanded state, and applies a lightweight residual transform. \n\n 3.2 Base architecture \n\n Base network follows a small-footprint SVDF-style architecture  [ alvarez19_icassp , nakkiran15_interspeech ] . Each Base (Encoder) Block applies SVDF, followed by batch-normalization (BN) [ ioffe15_pmlr ] , hard-swish  [ howard19_iccv ] , and dropout  [ hinton12_corr ] . The encoder output is temporally pooled and passed to an Core Head classifier producing logits\n\\ell_{\\mathrm{core}}^{\\mathrm{base}}(x)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{|\\mathcal{Y}_{1}|+1}\nover \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, followed by softmax. The base model has approximately 150k parameters (Fig.  1 ). \n\n 3.3 Modular expansion \n\n We freeze the entire base path (including BN affine parameters and running statistics) and attach a lightweight, trainable expansion path composed of L Expanded Blocks plus a New Head that predicts logits \\ell_{\\mathrm{new}}(x) over \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\} (Fig.  2 ). Expanded Blocks tap selected frozen Base Block activations (and optionally the previous Expanded Block output) and apply a small residual transform; the total added parameters (Expanded Blocks + New Head) are capped at 10k (final model \\sim160k parameters). \n\n Each Expanded Block takes the activation from a frozen Base Block and the previous Expanded Block output, concatenates them along the channel dimension, and applies a lightweight transform consisting of a 1D convolution (Conv1D over time, implemented as a small-kernel temporal conv), followed by batch-normalization and hard-swish.\nThe first Expanded Block is a special case: it takes only the frozen encoder activation (no previous expanded output), so the concatenation reduces to an identity.\nThe block output is then used as input to the next Expanded Block, and the final Expanded Block output is temporally pooled and fed to the New Head. \n\n The expanded model outputs \n\n \\displaystyle p_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) \n \\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}(\\ell_{\\mathrm{core}}(x)),\\quad y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, \n\n (1) \n\n \\displaystyle p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x) \n \\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}(\\ell_{\\mathrm{new}}(x)),\\quad y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. \n\n (2) \n\n Since the Core Head computation is frozen and does not depend on the expansion path, for all x: \n\n \\displaystyle\\ell^{\\mathrm{exp}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x) \n \\displaystyle\\equiv\\ell^{\\mathrm{base}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x), \n\n (3) \n\n \\displaystyle\\Rightarrow\\quad p^{\\mathrm{exp}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) \n \\displaystyle\\equiv p^{\\mathrm{base}}_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x),\\quad\\forall y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}. \n\n Training uses only D_{2} and updates only \\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}} by minimizing cross-entropy on the New Head: \n\n \\min_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{exp}}}\\ \\ \\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\\sim D_{2}}\\left[-\\log p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x)\\right]. \n\n (4) \n\n Table 1: Model size and the worst-case compute cost under the deployed inference pipeline (core-first decision rule) for 1-second utterance. \n\n Method \n Params (K) \n MACs (M) \n Rel. MACs \n\n Base Model \n 150 \n 15.08 \n 1.00\\times \n\n Full Finetune \n 150 \n 15.08 \n 1.00\\times \n\n EWC \n 150 \n 15.08 \n 1.00\\times \n\n Head-Only \n 151 \n 15.16 \n 1.01\\times \n\n Ensemble \n 160 \n 16.14 \n 1.07\\times \n\n Adapters \n 160 \n 18.45 \n 1.22\\times \n\n LoRA \n 160 \n 20.52 \n 1.36\\times \n\n Proposed \n 160 \n 16.34 \n 1.08\\times \n\n 3.4 Inference: core-first decision rule \n\n In a deployed KWS system, preserving the shipped behavior means preserving the\n decision rule of the original detector for the core label set\n\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}, not only its logits.\nWe therefore use a core-first decision rule. \n\n Let s^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y}(x)=p_{\\mathrm{core}}(y\\mid x) for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}\nand let \\tau^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y} denote the same per-keyword thresholds\nused by the shipped model.\nThe core detector outputs \n\n \\displaystyle y_{core}^{*}(x) \n \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}}s^{\\mathrm{core}}_{y}(x), \n\n (5) \n\n \\displaystyle\\hat{y}_{\\mathrm{core}}(x) \n \\displaystyle= \n\n Only if the core detector rejects (outputs \\emptyset) do we evaluate the new head.\nLet s^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}(x)=p_{\\mathrm{new}}(y\\mid x) for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}\nwith thresholds \\tau^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}. The expanded system outputs \n\n \\displaystyle y_{\\mathrm{new}}^{*}(x) \n \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}}s^{\\mathrm{new}}_{y}(x), \n\n (6) \n\n \\displaystyle\\hat{y}(x) \n \\displaystyle= \n\n 3.5 Baselines \n\n We compare against four baseline families that differ in whether they modify the\nshipped core detector and whether they can provide a strict non-regression\nguarantee. Unless stated otherwise, adaptation uses only D_{2} and all methods\nthat add capacity are constrained to \\leq10k new parameters. For completeness,\nTable  1 reports the parameter count and worst-case compute\ncost in multiply-accumulate operations (MACs) for each method under the deployed core-first inference pipeline; we\nuse these values to budget-match baselines and to quantify inference overhead. \n\n Unconstrained model updates. \n Full Finetune continues training the base model on D_{2} by updating\nall parameters with cross-entropy over \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}.\nThis serves as a reference for fitting the new keywords, but it generally\nintroduces catastrophic forgetting on \\mathcal{Y}_{1}. \n\n Core-invariant expansions (safe by construction). \n Head-Only trains only a new classifier head on top of the frozen base\nrepresentation (our method with L{=}0). Ensemble trains an independent\n\\sim10k-parameter model on D_{2} and combines it with the shipped detector using\nthe same core-first decision rule at inference. Both approaches preserve the core\ndetector exactly, but Head-only often lacks capacity, while Ensemble does not\nreuse the base model’s intermediate features. \n\n Parameter-efficient tuning with a forked branch. \n Adapters and LoRA introduce trainable modules in a parallel\ntop-L branch that feeds the New Head, while the original Core Head continues to\nuse the frozen base path. We choose L (and LoRA ranks) to match the additional\ninference compute of our expansion under the same 10k-parameter budget. \n\n Relaxed-constraint continual learning. \n EWC is included for context: it regularizes fine-tuning using Fisher\ninformation estimated from D_{1} and therefore does not strictly satisfy the\nno-access-to-D_{1} setting; we use \\lambda=5\\times 10^{5} in all experiments. \n\n Table 2: Macro FRR (%) on GSC test at thresholds calibrated to 1% FAR on CV,\nevaluated with the core-first decision rule. \n\n {left, right} \n {on, off} \n {stop, go} \n {up, down} \n {yes, no} \n Avg. \n\n Core Phrases \n\n Base Model \n\n 2.37 (±0.24) \n\n 2.42 (±0.31) \n\n 3.29 (±0.55) \n\n 2.63 (±0.28) \n\n 2.83 (±0.12) \n\n 2.71 (±0.12) \n\n Full Finetune \n 82.94 (±2.64) \n\n 79.68 (±7.79) \n\n 67.94 (±6.30) \n\n 54.33 (±13.55) \n\n 60.52 (±5.81) \n\n 69.08 (±1.98) \n\n EWC \n 7.07 (±0.62) \n\n 5.02 (±0.32) \n\n 3.06 (±0.53) \n\n 2.63 (±0.24) \n\n 4.56 (±0.16) \n\n 4.47 (±0.18) \n\n New Phrases \n\n Full Finetune \n 2.86 (±0.48) \n\n 2.14 (±0.46) \n\n 1.60 (±0.50) \n\n 3.33 (±0.70) \n\n 1.82 (±0.47) \n\n 2.35 (±0.27) \n\n Head-Only \n 42.55 (±16.44) \n\n 28.11 (±11.68) \n\n 18.61 (±10.88) \n\n 12.13 (±2.43) \n\n 10.11 (±2.20) \n\n 22.30 (±4.27) \n\n Ensemble \n 8.77 (±2.00) \n\n 3.81 (±0.99) \n\n 6.68 (±1.91) \n\n 5.82 (±0.73) \n\n 7.21 (±1.17) \n\n 6.46 (±0.42) \n\n EWC \n\n 5.44 (±0.40) \n\n 6.97 (±1.08) \n\n 5.96 (±0.57) \n\n 12.28 (±1.89) \n\n 9.09 (±1.18) \n\n 7.95 (±0.64) \n\n Adapters \n 13.38 (±1.68) \n\n 8.95 (±1.61) \n\n 6.68 (±2.01) \n\n 5.74 (±0.65) \n\n 5.52 (±0.80) \n\n 8.05 (±0.35) \n\n LoRA \n 9.88 (±1.36) \n\n 5.84 (±1.28) \n\n 6.61 (±2.11) \n\n 5.12 (±1.78) \n\n 4.61 (±0.86) \n\n 6.41 (±0.66) \n\n Proposed \n 6.69 (±1.04) \n\n 2.68 (±0.39) \n\n 4.56 (±0.86) \n\n 4.57 (±0.73) \n\n 3.36 (±0.38) \n\n 4.37 (±0.33) \n\n Figure 3: New-keyword FRR (%) vs. Expanded Blocks L for \\mathcal{Y}_{2}=\\{\\textit{left,right}\\}. \n\n 4 Experiments \n\n 4.1 Datasets and expansion tasks \n\n Experiments are conducted on Google Speech Commands v2 (GSC) using the official train/validation/test splits. The target vocabulary is the standard set of 10 commands\n{ left, right, on, off, stop, go, up, down, yes, no }.\nAll other words in GSC, together with silence segments, are mapped to the background label \\emptyset. \n\n Keyword expansion is evaluated through five held-out pairs to reduce sensitivity to any single keyword choice and to cover a range of confusability patterns. For each task, one command pair is designated as the new set \\mathcal{Y}_{2} and the remaining eight commands form the deployed core set \\mathcal{Y}_{1}. The held-out pairs are\n{left, right}, {on, off}, {stop, go}, {up, down}, and {yes, no}.\nA base model is trained on D_{1} (GSC train restricted to \\mathcal{Y}_{1}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}). The expansion stage then uses only D_{2} (GSC train restricted to \\mathcal{Y}_{2}\\cup\\{\\emptyset\\}), with no access to the original D_{1} audio. \n\n To obtain a less biased negative distribution than GSC itself, Mozilla Common Voice v17 (CV) [ ardila-etal-2020-common ] is used as a negative-only corpus. In all reported results, positives come from the GSC test split, while negatives for FAR calibration come from the CV test split. \n\n 4.2 Features and training setup \n\n Audio is 16 kHz mono. Input features are 40-bin log-mel filterbanks computed with a 25 ms window and 10 ms hop. To improve robustness to channel and speaking-style variability, training applies SpecAugment [ park19e_interspeech ] directly on the log-mel features (time masking and frequency masking). \n\n Optimization uses Adam [ kingma14_iclr ] with a cosine learning-rate schedule [ loshchilov17_iclr ] . Base Models are trained for 40 epochs on D_{1}. Expansion training runs for 10 epochs on D_{2}. For modular methods (including the proposed one), only the newly added parameters are updated during expansion; the base path is kept frozen, including batch-normalization affine parameters and running statistics. Methods that introduce new capacity are constrained to an added-parameter budget of \\leq10k. \n\n 4.3 Metric, thresholds, and confidence intervals \n\n Performance is reported as macro false reject rate (FRR) at a fixed false accept rate (FAR) operating point. For each keyword y, a threshold \\tau_{y} is chosen to match 1% FAR on the CV test partition, using the corresponding keyword score (Core Head for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{1}, New Head for y\\in\\mathcal{Y}_{2}). \n\n Given calibrated thresholds, FRR is computed on the GSC test split. Reported values are macro-averaged across the keywords in the evaluated set (core or new). \n\n Each (method, keyword-pair) configuration is repeated with 8 independent runs (different random seeds). Table  2 reports the sample mean and a 95% confidence interval estimated via a t-statistic:\n\\bar{x}\\ \\pm\\ t_{0.975,7}\\,s/\\sqrt{8},\nwhere s is the sample standard deviation across runs. \n\n 4.4 Comparative analysis \n\n Table  2 reports macro FRR (%) on GSC positives with\nthresholds calibrated to 1% FAR on CV negatives (95% confidence intervals in\nparentheses). \n\n The Base Model achieves low FRR on the core vocabulary (from 2.37% to 3.29%,\n2.71% on average). The Core Phrases section includes only methods that\ncan change the shipped detector (Full Fine-tuning and EWC). Adapters, LoRA,\nEnsemble, and the proposed method freeze the core path, so their core results\nmatch the Base Model exactly and are omitted to avoid repeating identical\nnumbers. \n\n Full Fine-tuning fits the new phrases well (2.35% average FRR) but catastrophically\nregresses the core vocabulary, increasing average core FRR from 2.71% \nto 69.08% . EWC mitigates forgetting but still increases core FRR to\n 4.47% ; on new phrases it reaches 7.95% on average (best case\n5.44% on {left, right}). We include EWC for context, although it relies on\ninformation derived from D_{1} (or precomputed Fisher statistics) and thus\nviolates the strict no-D_{1} setting. \n\n Among methods that satisfy the deployment constraints, Head-Only performs poorly\non new keywords ( 22.30% average FRR). Parameter-efficient baselines\nimprove substantially, with Adapters at 8.05% and LoRA at\n 6.41% . Ensemble is a strong deployment baseline that adds an\nindependent \\sim10k-parameter model for \\mathcal{Y}_{2}, achieving\n 6.46% . Modular expansion further improves new-keyword detection under\nthe same parameter budget, reducing average FRR to 4.37% (an absolute\ngain of 2.09 points). \n\n 4.5 Ablation Study: Expansion Depth \n\n We analyze the impact of feature reuse depth in Figure 3 , which plots new-keyword FRR against the number of tapped blocks in the expansion path. Tapping only shallow layers (1–3 blocks) yields high error rates, suggesting insufficient semantic abstraction. Conversely, extending the expansion to four blocks minimizes the median FRR. Beyond this point, performance plateaus or slightly degrades, indicating that the deepest layers of the base network are overly specialized to the core vocabulary Y_{1} and provide limited transfer utility. Consequently, we adopt the four-block expansion as the optimal configuration for all reported comparisons. \n\n 5 Conclusion \n\n On-device KWS systems must evolve as products add features and languages, yet\nupdates are challenging when the original training audio cannot be reused and\nregressions on existing keywords are unacceptable. \n\n We presented a modular expansion mechanism that adds new keywords without\ntouching the deployed detector. The full base network is kept frozen (including\nbatch-normalization statistics), and new functionality is introduced through a\nsmall attached branch and a separate new-keyword head (up to 10k parameters),\nkeeping the core detector’s logits and threshold behavior exactly unchanged. \n\n On Google Speech Commands (thresholds calibrated at 1% FAR using Common Voice),\nthe expanded model improves average new-keyword FRR from 6.46% to\n 4.37% versus a parameter-matched separate-model baseline and also\noutperforms adapter- and LoRA-based tuning. It further uses fewer worst-case\nMACs under the deployed core-first pipeline ( 16.34M ) than adapters\n( 18.45M ) and LoRA ( 20.52M ) at the same added-parameter budget. Together, these results\nsupport modular expansion as a practical way to scale embedded KWS vocabularies\nwhile preserving the shipped user experience. \n\n Multi-stage expansion, where new keyword sets are added sequentially, is a\nnatural direction for future work, especially under tight parameter and latency budgets. \n\n 6 Generative AI Use Disclosure \n\n We used ChatGPT (OpenAI; GPT-5.2) to assist with English editing and polishing of the manuscript. All technical content, experiments, and conclusions were produced and verified by the authors. \n\n References \n\n Experimental support, please\n view the build logs \n for errors. Generated by\n\n L\n A \n T\n E \n\n xml \n\n .\n\n Instructions for reporting errors \n We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile\n support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the\n methods listed below: \n\n Click the \"Report Issue\" ( \n\n ) button, located in the page header. \n\n Tip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report. \n Our team has already identified the following issues . We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we\n may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability\n should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for\n all. \n Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion , and welcome developer contributions . \n\n We gratefully acknowledge support from\n our major funders ,\n member institutions , ,\n and all contributors.\n\n About \n · \n Help \n · \n Contact \n · \n Subscribe \n · \n Copyright \n · \n Privacy \n · \n Accessibility \n · \n Operational Status (opens in new tab) \n\n Major funding support from \n\n", "numLines": 578, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 578}}}
